        "id": 185229,
        "name": "Jonathan Andreas",
        "username": "JonathanAndreas",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/community.signalusers.org/jonathanandreas/{size}/31766_2.png",
        "created_at": "2022-08-01T20:21:49.079Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Signal‚Äôs ‚ÄòForward‚Äô function is confusing for new users because it doesn‚Äôt behave like forwarding in email and most other communication technologies even going all the way back to snailmail.  It is also confusing for new users because it doesn‚Äôt work analogously to how Signal‚Äôs ‚ÄòReply‚Äô function works and the two functions use exactly the same arrow icon which indicates that they should work the same way, but they are completely different.<br>\nSignal‚Äôs ‚ÄòForward‚Äô function really means copy text for broadcasting.  This is unlike email forwarding and Signal‚Äôs ‚ÄòReply‚Äô function which both re-send a message as a quote which shows who originally wrote the message.<br>\nSignal‚Äôs ‚ÄòForward‚Äô function is really useful, but it would be better to also add a ‚ÄòForward quote‚Äô function that works the way email works (a[nd how Signal‚Äôs ‚ÄòReply‚Äô works).  In fact, if we had that, then we wouldn‚Äôt need a ‚ÄòReply to sender‚Äô function.  (See <a href=\"https://community.signalusers.org/t/reply-vs-reply-all/46213/2\">https://community.signalusers.org/t/reply-vs-reply-all/46213/2</a>)<br>\nExtreme privacy advocates might argue that this could compromise privacy, but it is already easy to forward screenshots of Signal messages and this would essentially work the same way.  It would just make it easier to forward quotes.</p>",
        "post_number": 1,
        "post_type": 1,
        "posts_count": 3,
        "updated_at": "2022-08-01T20:22:08.851Z",
